Are weather and delays correlated?

Consider the nycflights13 package, and the join between the average daily delay and the weather on that day. The following code block makes available this information.

# this block of code is the solution to last week's exercise
average_delay <- flights %>% 
  drop_na(dep_delay) %>% 
  group_by(origin, year, month, day) %>%
  summarise(dep_delay = mean(dep_delay))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'origin', 'year', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
weather_delay <- weather %>%
  drop_na(wind_speed, temp, precip) %>%
  group_by(origin, year, month, day) %>%
  summarise(
    wind_speed = mean(wind_speed),
    temp = mean(temp),
    precip = mean(precip)
  ) %>% 
  inner_join(average_delay, by=c("origin", "year", "month", "day"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'origin', 'year', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Can you spot any correlations?

Now try to represent several variables in the dataset at once in the same plot. In particular, represent in a single scatterplot the wind_speed, the temp, the precip and the dep_delay. Remember that you can use several different aesthetic channels at the same time, one for each different variable. Examples of the aesthetics you might want to use are x, y, size, color, shape.

# Your solution here

  • Try to plot the average delay against the month. What can you conclude? Hint: you can either compute the average delay in the preprocessing pipeline using group_by and
    summarise or you can use the stat = "summary" argument to geom_point or geom_bar.
# your solution 
average_delay <- flights%>% group_by(month)%>%summarise(average_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = T))%>%
ggplot(mapping = aes(y = average_delay, x = month)) + geom_smooth(na.rm = T) + geom_point(na.rm = T)

  • What about plotting the delay against the day of the year (thus ranging from 1 to 365)? You can use the days dataframe provided below to get the day of the year. Remember that there are several flights per day, so you will have to take the average delay for each day of the year.
days <- flights %>%
  distinct(month, day)%>%
  arrange(month, day) %>%
  mutate(day_of_year = row_number())

days <- flights %>%
